segments.text: Some of them, they just take it, give everything they had up.
They're going off.
You want to send it up?
They see it is going, sure enough, they beg you to stay, you know, another year.
Get anything you want, any kind of money.
But now you're going to stay there next year because your crop ain't going to occur, you know.
It's not going to occur.
You let your stand.
And feed you to the hives.
Now have children like this girl here, this any kind of dress she wore, they let you take it up.
But now when the crop come, they'll take a little bit of that crop.
You wouldn't have nothing to live on next year until next year come.
Well, that old McCown was right there for Christmas, you know, get just what you wanted.
That's what they do in places over there.
But there was sure fine white folks over there.
Before you'd wake up, I had one round over there.
And that was about some Johnson graves.
What was that?
You know, Johnson grass after a flood, you know, just seeds washed all over the field.
Well, next year, they'd come up just digging that.
That's why I wouldn't want you to cut it up.
You want to go over the field and pull it up.
It's all over the field.
Pull it up every spread, you know.
It comes up, you know, like shovel.
And pull it up.
And I wouldn't pull it up.
I'd go across the field digging up like...
And he wanted me to pull a root and oil up, you know.
He told me I was too old for that.
I couldn't do it.
He said, well, if you can't pull this up, when you get this crop off, you'll leave.
Leave my place.
I said, thank you, sir.
Well, everybody got the crop, you know, made a good crop that year.
Got the crop, he went on to see his wife.
And his wife come down there one day and says, Laura, said, ma'am, can you take me to leave?
I said, yes, and this time I get this crop out, I'm going to leave, too.
Said Mr. Payne was drunk, I wouldn't leave.
I said, yes ma'am, I'm going to leave.
I'll leave this place.
I said, Mr. Payne, come in the field sometime.
You wouldn't be with him.
Jump on me, kill me.
Beat me to death.
I said, oh no, she said, I wouldn't leave.
But see, I done got scared then, you know.
He told me to leave.
And I'd been there then.
I'd been on his place in 16 years.
And it's the first time he ever told me to leave, you know.
And I just got scared, you know.
And I left now.
I left in the house.
Sometimes those landlords would whip them, they say.
He'd fight them.
He'd fight the hands.
He would?
Yes.
They wouldn't let him whip them.
They'd fight him.
He wouldn't try to hurt none of them, but he'd jump down on his horse to fight them, you know.
And the hands would fight him.
The men would fight him.
And he sure was a good old white man, though.
And he'd go to the house on his horse to get a gun, get a gun at him.
And he'd ride right in the field and come back with his gun, you know, right up ahead of us.
Well, Albert followed me a while ago, so-and-so followed me a while ago, and I'm going back killing him.
I wouldn't do that.
I wouldn't have it in the name of killing my hands on the place.
I wouldn't have it to say I hurt none of my hands on the place and they stayed there.
And you don't have no trouble with that.
Yes, that's so.
All right, God, do it again.
I'm going to kill him.
We'll be sure to go to the white man.
We jumped once.
We was in the wagon.
We jumped once.
Got his gun.
Could have did it.
Got his gun and shoot in the wagon with me and my children.
And his wife hanging to the Winchester by the door.
Who was he going to shoot at?
They were going to shoot in the wagon at us.
Said, my boy, you know, put the dog on his dog.
You know how dogs is?
You go across by the road.
Said, put it on his dog.
You got to shoot at him.
And she hanging to him.
Said, don't you shoot that rag.
You kill all of them children.
I'll kill all of them.
One dog jump on my dog.
And this time, she got the gun away from him.
Went right back and laid down there.
Said, no, don't worry.
He was just that.
She wants to have time handling him.
Yes.
He was good.
They were good people.
But here's fractures, whoop, here's fractures.

If you brought out a load of corn, first and foremost, you know, if you brought out a load of corn, and if it wasn't just level, you'd be not bringing that load out all level, you'd have to take some off that corn, first and foremost, so it'd give you the little one.
Like you said, Mr. Payne, there's your corn.
Oh, sir, I don't want it.
I don't want it.
That corn ain't full load.
I don't want it.
He wouldn't have it near.
No sir.
But he was sure good folks.
But he sure was fractious.
He was too fractious.
But he was good people.
And therefore he'd better round than drink him.
That way his wife wouldn't stay at the house and he'd come to the field.
He'd have come with him.
Because you know she's going to have a round with some of the colored folks.
Is that right?
Yes.
Right down there in that bottom, too.
Around with the colorful.
And she'd come along with him.
She'd come along with him every time.
If he walked, she'd walk with him.
If he ran in a wagon, anything, she'd come, too.
Oh, he was so mean.
He'd fracture that away when he got drinking.
Did he ever try to whip any of them with a whip?
No, he never tried to whip them with no whip, nothing like that.
But he'd jump right down, be plowing.
He's more out of his half-hands than anybody else.
Be plowing, you know, and they wouldn't talk to suit him.
He'd jump right down by the plow with no way to move.
He'd go in off and don't commit to knocking him, you know.
And they couldn't commit to knocking him, touching him, too.
But anything after he'd fight one of them, they'd fight him, too.
Fight one of them, and he'd go out to the house and come to the lock.
See, they're just as good, you know.
Just as good, you know.
He said, well, Sandy come.
Let's go to town and drink it off.
Let's go to town, boy, and drink it off.
They had it wrong with them then all that week.
He was good for them.
They'd go to town.
But he let them go to church any time they wanted to?
Yeah, so they went to church.
He didn't bother about no church, nothing like that.
He had a church right there on his place.
Right there on his place.
He must have had a lot of hands working for him.
He had a big plantation.
I think he had 700 acres.
He had them.
He had 14 houses on the page.
They were there to call a page, please.
He never bothered.
One white man tried to project a church, and that was Mr. Morton.
He tried to project a colorful church.
Why?
He didn't want them to have a church on the page, you know.
He didn't want them to have it.
Now, you ask me any words you want to ask about the exclave, you know, back, and I can remember.
Well, ain't had about how old are you?
Well, I don't know, Mr. Elkwood.
We don't know my age, only by the children telling us.
My mom died, and she didn't know nothing about our age.
But the children traced back from the exclave up to now.
Well, how old were you when you were... Well, I was about 13 years old at the breakup.
Uh-huh.
And you remember slavery days very well?
Of course, I remember all our white folks and all the names of them, all the children.
Called every one of the children's names.
Who did you belong to?
Jim Brunson, the baby boy.
Where was that?
Where did he live?
Back out here in Haines County.
How many slaves did he have?
Well, he had my grandma and...
And my ma, my ma was a cook.
And grandma, you know, and then they worked in the field.
And everything, I remember when she used to plow oxen.
I plowed, I plowed oxen myself.
Is that right?
I can plow and lay off a corn row as good as any man.
Is that right?
I used to pick cotton.
I used to pick, well, I've been here ever since I've been here.
A hundred of them picked my 500 pounds of cotton.
Knock out 500 pounds.
Knock out 500 pounds of cotton.
It won't cost a few.
And hunt watermelons and plum granules.
Yeah.
Do you remember church times?
Yes, I remember church times.
You were 20 for a time.
Yes, I remember our folks.
They had power meetings from one house to another.
The colored folks.
Yes.
Uh-huh.
The people there.
You know, the houses, you know, would be in sections.
And the house was in different places.
They'd go, and we'd have priming.
More important than good priming.
And dances, too.
And dances, too?
Yes.
I've seen far more dancing in the meantime.
Is that a doing slavery thing?
Well, my grandma, too.
My grandma was named Rachel Proctor.
Rachel Proctor.
Yes, but she belonged to the Bunnies.
That's what she meant by her husband's name.
Yeah, yes, I knew his back.
Now, in slavery time, there was my sister, my brother was slaved back.
And all of them stayed with me, one, one of the girls, and she lived in San Antonio, Adelaide Taylor.
Adelaide Taylor, so she was your sister?
Yes, she was in the young bunch.
Sister Ida, and she was the next, Brother George,
And Sister Ida and myself were slaves.
And others were born free.
And all of them, we were only two slaves.
Well, I'm glad.
Did you go to meetings?
Did you ever go to church?
We would go to big cast, prime meetings, you know.
We used to show them to us in the corner, you know.
We used to have a good opportunity.
Is that right?
Yes, they cast the family.
Well, did you go to the white folks' church any?
Yes, I went to Mountain City to the white folks' church many times.
See, the white folks would have church in the morning, then we'd let the colored people have church at their church in the evening.
That's your slavery.
In the slave time.
In the slave time.
Yes, as well.
Well, what would the preacher preach about in those days?
I don't know.
I doesn't go.
What does the preacher preach about, you know?
There you go.
He didn't preach like the dudes, did he?
No, they weren't made to teach, you know, and they all raised how to be, how to get along, you know, how to treat the white people and so on.
And they used the Bible, them, you know.
Yeah, I remember all about it in slavery time.
Born there, we used to go to dances, white folks.
Well, did the white folks treat you good?
How, for the boys?
Uh-huh.
They was good to us.
They never hooked none of their colored people.
Our colored people, they'd take their saddle horse, Mrs. Brown's saddle horse, big girl, Anna, and she'd have them ride.
Grandma wouldn't ride from Mountain City to church.
They had white preachers then.
Mr. Porter, he was one of the preachers that lived across from us.
Well, would the white preachers tell you to behave yourselves and be good to your master?
Yes, that's what they preached.
We really didn't know it was any such thing.
It was God, and in the name of God, you know, we thought that was a different man.
But he was our master, our white folks, you know, the preachers who was the white folks' master, and so on that way.
He said, well, that's all the better.
Well, all of them would go up by the church and ask to come to be free, you know.
They came to preach it, you know.
They came to know, you know, there was a God, and so on.
Well, while you all were slaves, did they teach you to read and write?
Did you all go to church?
Nuh-uh.
Nuh-uh.
They didn't know nothing about reading and writing.
All that I know, they teach you to mind your master and your master.
They sure didn't teach you to read and write.
No, they didn't.
Pick cotton, I remember, picking cotton.
Well, did you ever hear of any slaves being mistreated?
Were there any tales going around?
Yes, I know of times of mistreated people they did.
I hear our folks talking about them hooting and all.
So they had to squeeze the back, to take the clothes from the back.
Good Lord have mercy.
My folks, that way.
But them business sure didn't allow them colored people to be hooted.
And they halted, they started halted.
Mr. Duncan's Saddle Horse and Ma and Pa and Ma and Ma and the Green Horse, they rode their horses in the saddle.
Mountain City Church.
And the children stayed home.
And from that on then, from one to another, began to learn palm teaching and amongst them.
They'd have a prayer meeting, you know, from one house to the other.
You know, at the house, like there's a house sitting here in a section in line, you know, and people would come to the prayer meeting.
And on Sunday in the evening, the white folks let the preacher preach, because our folks were the dead church preachers.
Well, do you remember any of the songs they sang in those days at churches?
No.
If I had the books, I could remember and look and see.
They sang the song, Are We Born to Die?
They'd sing that.
Are We Born to Die?
How'd that go, you know?
That's right, the Secretary-Council we gave.
Now, a little while.
Yes, yes.
How did it go?
Yes.
They say I was born to die.
First Secretary-Council I was given.
I was living.
I was sitting back.
I never read much.
We children, we stayed at home, parched corn, and played, you know.
More and more of them grandmas ride the horses and about three miles from our home, white folks' home, where they stay, and go to the white folks' church.
I used to hear them laugh and tell it all the time, you know.
We didn't know anything about freedom at all.
It was free that I was me and my oldest, next oldest sister, my brother George.
He was there all day, all those days, but just two of us.
Well, can you remember when the war was going on?
Of course I can.
I sat on the fence.
At the time, me and Cousin Lou and Cousin Sally and all of us, our lodge had white picket fence right along by our house, like the road goes along by my house.
We sat on it, I stood on that picket fence all day long seeing them soldiers going back to San Antonio, a different place.
I had to put in their gloves and beavers.
And horses would swing and dance and fall just like that.
What are you doing?
Culling soldiers.
Culling soldiers?
Well, culling soldiers in droves.
That's right along by our house.
Our home is a two-story house, a white brook's home, you know.
And we stayed on the home until we bought the homes over across the creek while we lived in Portland.
I remember a long time ago, you told me about during the big breakup, the soldiers came by and riding horseback.
And you all were sitting on the fence, you children.
Can you remember that?
Yeah.
Lean this way just a little bit and tell about it.
Yes, I knew that.
I sat down all day and looked at them.
They played a few of this music, you know, this joy in your life.
And so it was, you know, and them horses, they'd sing, you know.
And them horses duck and fall on their knees just like that.
Oh, wow.
Adam Train.
Yeah, Adam Train.
Well, what about this girl you told me about that one?
Well, that photo was the one that Long Miss photo, one of our white folks in there.
And she got her own ground horse and molasses mill, feeding molasses mills.
How was that?
How do you mean feeding the molasses?
Putting that cane in there for it to grind out to make molasses.
Oh, yeah.
Grinding out juice, huh?
Yeah, juice.
They had them wooden corks or things, you know, master canes back then.
And they'd hitch a mule to it, wouldn't they?
Yes.
And he'd walk in a circle.
Yes, yes.
He'd walk in a circle.
Yes, have a lever to it, you know, and go round and round.
Uh-huh.
We've made molasses that way.
I've made molasses myself.
You have?
Well, now this girl got her arm drowned off in molasses.
Yes, feeding the molasses mill.
That was in another neighborhood.
Well, how old was she?
Oh, she was a great big girl.
She was about big enough to feed the mill.
About 10 or 12 years old, I think.
Maybe a little older than that.
And the men would have molasses and pour it.
She made molasses for everybody in there.
That girl had that milled feet.
Can't have canes, you know, great big piles, piled up.
She had to reach down and get that and put it in between the corks.
When that grinded out, she'd pick up another handful and put it in there.
Well, did they have good doctors for them in those days?
When it ground off her arm, what did they do?
How did they get her out?
I don't know.
I guess they carried her on their own.
I remember Dr. Manilow and Dr. Cavanaugh.
I remember them.
Well, when the soldiers came by, where was she?
Who, Matt?
Uh-huh.
She was on the other side.
She lived the other side of us.
She was living, she was living with our white people.
But this road went right along by our white people's house.
I can go right to the day before I was born there.
It was cut right along by the house.
They did all day for weeks at the time.
There was so many of us traveling going south to Silent Hill.
Oh, they had the prettiest horses you most ever saw.
Well, now, what did those girls, what did this girl, Matt, do?
Matt told her?
Uh-huh.
Well, she fed the mail.
Well, I mean, though, when the soldiers came by.
Why, she's on the fence by with us, looking at them.
She lived right across from us, you know, and that was the road.
Well, I thought she went off with the soldiers.
She did.
She went off with the soldiers.
The soldiers come along.
We're all sitting on the fence.
And I stand at the fence sitting.
And a colored soldier come along and asked her, did she want to go with us?
And she said, yes.
She miles one of them horses.
Not behind him?
No, it was a horse to herself.
Is that right?
We could ride horses.
We'd jump on them horses.
Started some time riding, some time we learned how to do it.
I could stand flat footed on the ground and jump on the horse's side with it.
Is that right?
Right, right, yeah.
Well, you were riding.
Yes, all of us, all of we always raced to ride horses.
Paul had horses of his own, chickens of his own.
Well, then what happened to Mack Porter after she and that soldier?
She was on with them.
I never did see her and hit that over no more.
She was going towards San Tom.
Going towards San Tom?
Yes, she was on with them.
Well, what did she do?
Didn't even go tell her mama she was going or anything?
She didn't have any mother.
Oh, I see.
And she'd already been freed, had she?
Yes, yes.
That was the time the soldiers was going back, you know, after the field.
Mm-hmm.
She'd always come over to our house and stay with us.
Well, can you remember the times right after the big breakup very well?
Remember, were times pretty hard then?
Yes, times were hard.
Our white folks weren't mean to their colored people.
It was different for them.
There were seven brothers of them.
There was Shea Bunton, John Bunton, Bob Bunton.
We had one, one, one, Kentucky Joe, so on, a whole pack of them.
Seven brothers of them, I know.
Some of them lived at Cedar Creek.
More or no, the more I know.
Well, what did y'all do after the big breakup?
Did y'all leave the place?
No, we stayed on the place and rented on the half.
Oh, rented on the half.
All our fight folks was dead.
And the old C was, oh, the...
Breed love.
I, Tom, I breed love.
I breed love.
Mountain City.
That's our old, old, old sale was a place, you know.
And you all rented on the house.
Rented on the house, too.
We bought our home across the creek.
Oh, you bought your home.
About how long after the big breakup did y'all buy it?
Oh, I didn't buy it.
We didn't buy it.
Paul bought the home from old Riley across the creek, and we stayed down there.
I used to stay with Aunt Rose and Uncle George.
They were old folks, had no children, you know.
They used to get me to come and stay with them.
And when I married, they gave me a home on the place.
Well, were they white folks?
No, colored folks.
Oh, good.
Well, how old were you when you married?
Well, I don't know.
17, 18 years old.
Maybe that old.
I didn't know my age.
Who did you marry?
Jim Smith.
Jim Smith.
Had he been a slave?
Oh, yes.
He was a slave.
After the breakup, they sent him.
He come from Blackpool and bought a home over across the creek while we bought a home, Johnny, and our home.
His father and mother did, you know.
Well, he had been freed then, I guess, the
at the same time you had.
Oh, yes, yes.
They lived at Blanco.
They bought them a home over in the colony.
Riley had sold the colored people all the homes there.
I don't know.
Who was Riley?
A white man named Riley lived right down the hill from us.
They sold Pete Bradley homes and Paul homes, Uncle David homes.
Oh, all of them.
Well, I'm glad.
And that was right after the big break-up, was it?
About two, three years after the break-up.
Huh.
And you just had a colony of...
Yes, all that colony.
Where I come from, it's got homes out there.
That's Buda, they called it now.
It was nothing but woods when we bought it.
They called it Buda then?
Yes.
Oh, I know where Buda is.
Yes, yes, yes.
Did you know Mr. Talley in those days?
I think I did know Mr. Talley.
Huh.
What was he?
He was a deputy sheriff, that's why.
Is that right?
Yes.
He was my fine man, too.
Yeah.
Sure is.
And you remember, can you remember churches very well in Hatton?
Were you a church goer?
No, we used to show them then when slavery time.
My mother and father, I can remember when they went to church.
Our white folks, they'd ride to go to church in the morning, you know.
And they'd go in the evening, my grandma, to the white folks' church.
And they'd ride their horses.
Well, then when did you start going to church?
Oh, yeah, I never started going to church.
We never had any church until much after I married.
Well, and you started going, didn't you?
After you got married?
How did you marry?
Did you have a preacher marry you?
Of course, a white preacher married us.
He did?
A white preacher married all of us girls.
There wasn't any preacher much when I married.
Well, who did you...
When did you first start going to church then?
Well, we'd go to church then, and we had church before, before it was locked.
You know, preachers didn't know anything, you know, on what they hid.
Was he a traveling preacher, or was he just a colored preacher?
Yes, just traveling, you know, and stopping to preach.
There was a haywood, and groins, and so that was our preacher's name.
Well, what would you preach about?
Can you remember?
Well, they just preached that we had a God and a soul to be saved and so on.
Did the preacher preach today?
Oh, no.
They didn't know nothing.
They only read the Bible sometimes in places they could read.
No, they weren't.
The priest wasn't educated to talk.
They weren't, huh?
No, on the spell.
Some of them was reading right talk.
No, the spell, the letter, and so on.
They were reading right talk.
Some of them couldn't read and write at all, just only the priests.
What they could ever say, you know.
Then some of them laughed at getting older and wiser, you know.
Well, what about the songs that they sang?
That's what I'm interested in.
I didn't go much into the songs.
Well, they sang these old 100s.
You know what an old 100 means?
Yeah, these old-time songs.
Uh-huh.
Yeah.
Well, they're lying off one, you know.
It's Jesus, bear the cross alone, and all the world will go free.
Yeah, yeah.
That's the end going, I say.
There's no way of speaking to you like that.
You're treated by them.
Yeah.
Yes, he sang them songs.
I had the old-time books, hymn books.
Well, where would you get those books?
They had them selling them.
My grandma and them bought them, you know.
My husband bought eight people.
Jim Booker.
Was your husband, Henry Smith, much of a... Jim Smith?
Oh, Jim Smith.
Mm-hmm.
Was he a church man?
Yes, he was.
What happened to him?
Church man, church man, a politic man, too.
Oh, they were.
Y'all voted in those days.
Yes, my husband was in it.
He was run by a high school.
He was well up there.
When he got killed, the white folk was just crazy about him.
They come pretty soon.
That boy that killed my husband, I nursed him when he was a baby.
How come he didn't kill your husband?
Well, he's just mean.
Just mean, you know.
And they didn't like people up to date, you know.
And of course, it was just 13 months until my husband killed his brother.
Stole him.
Killed his last brother.
Mm-hmm.
He'd been to church.
I think he went to jail that night to carry a barrel of cotton.
And this Walter Byers sat down on the seat and the whole class of them was sitting down talking.
And when the time had come to his cotton, they killed him.
And they killed my brother, my husband, on the way from Cedar Bay.
I go right to the spot now, and that's why he was killed there.
Shot him or killed him?
Shot him.
Shot him on the way from Cedar Bay.
See, we'd have a Cedar Bay at home after we went home.
Well, what kind of politics did he do?
Well, he worked for white people when they wanted to be elected, you know, in the state at that time.
He worked amongst the colored folks.
Amongst the colored people.
He didn't speak to white folks.
He couldn't get in the house when he spoke hardly to white people.
All that sex in there.
He had a good life.
He had all of them boys there.
And he'd round up the votes, and that's how come them to kill him.
And when he sat the night for a speech, people from Austin, from San Marcos, from everywhere to be white and colored to hear him speak.
He'd go to the courthouse and speak for them.
Well, did the colored folks not like him?
No, the colored people all went.
that these white people, this boy that killed him, who walked by, I nursed him when he was a baby before I was ever acquainted with my husband.
Well, what I'm trying to find out is, how come he didn't kill your husband?
Was it over politics?
Oh, politics and different things, you know.
Poor white people.
Did the white folks have your husband killed, or did...
Did he just walk by and just go shoot himself?
No, my husband went to the break that day.
And on his way back from the city break, he ran through the road and killed him.
And I said, there's something about the horse.
I don't know how that is done, but the white people, Walter Kaiser, the name of the first one that got to him when he was killed, they had to shoot him.
They brought the news to us.
My brother and them.
What'd they do to Walter Biles?
Well, you know why?
That's what he lived up in there, you know.
They could tell any kind of tale.
They didn't do nothing with him.
Had him up.
Put him in jail.
But his brother-in-law killed him.
Is that right?
Sure.
They must have been shooting a lot of folk up in those days.
Poor people, you know.
Rich white people don't bother nobody.
Or poor white folks.
Yeah, it was poor.
And they come out.
And his brother-in-law said Lawson killed him.
Said his father moved away.
He had a good home over there.
And they moved away.
Said they'd steal his life.
Just like they stole Bud's and Jim's.
